# Technical Specifications

## Technology Stack

### Core Framework

- **Framework:** Next.js (React-based framework)
- **React Version:** React 18+
- **Language:** JavaScript/TypeScript (prefer TypeScript for new code)

### Styling

- **Primary:** Tailwind CSS for utility-first styling
- **Alternative Options:** 
  - CSS Modules for component-scoped styles
  - Styled-Components for CSS-in-JS (when needed for dynamic styling)
- **Preference:** Use Tailwind CSS as the primary styling solution

### Build & Development Tools

- **Package Manager:** npm (or yarn/pnpm)
- **Build Tool:** Next.js built-in (Webpack/Turbopack)
- **Code Quality:** ESLint + Prettier
- **Accessibility:** ESLint JSX A11y plugin

## File Structure

### Next.js App Router Structure (Recommended)

```
/
  ├─ app/                    # Next.js App Router (if using App Router)
  │   ├─ layout.jsx
  │   ├─ page.jsx
  │   ├─ about/
  │   ├─ services/
  │   └─ ...
  ├─ src/                     # Alternative: Pages Router
  │   ├─ components/
  │   ├─ pages/
  │   ├─ styles/
  │   └─ utils/
  ├─ public/                  # Static assets
  ├─ styles/                  # Global styles (if using CSS Modules)
  └─ .next/                   # Next.js build output
```

### Component Organization

- **Components:** `src/components/` or `components/`
- **Pages:** `src/pages/` (Pages Router) or `app/` (App Router)
- **Styles:** `src/styles/` for global, component-level for CSS Modules
- **Utils:** `src/utils/` for helper functions
- **Data/Config:** `src/data/` for static data

## Code Standards

### React Best Practices

- **Functional Components:** Use functional components with hooks exclusively
- **Hooks:** Prefer built-in hooks, create custom hooks for reusable logic
- **Component Structure:** 
  ```jsx
  // Component structure
  import React from 'react'
  import styles from './Component.module.css' // if using CSS Modules
  
  const Component = ({ prop1, prop2 }) => {
    // Hooks
    // Logic
    // Return JSX
  }
  
  export default Component
  ```

### Styling Approach

#### Tailwind CSS (Primary)

- Use utility classes for styling
- Create custom components for repeated patterns
- Use `@apply` sparingly in CSS files
- Configure Tailwind theme in `tailwind.config.js`

#### CSS Modules (When Needed)

- Use for component-scoped styles
- File naming: `Component.module.css`
- Import: `import styles from './Component.module.css'`
- Use: `className={styles.className}`

#### Styled-Components (Optional)

- Use for dynamic, theme-based styling
- Use for complex animations or conditional styles
- Prefer Tailwind for static styling

### Code Organization

- **Modular:** Keep components small and focused
- **Reusable:** Extract common patterns into shared components
- **Separation of Concerns:** Separate UI, logic, and data
- **DRY Principle:** Don't repeat yourself
- **Single Responsibility:** Each component/function should do one thing well

## Performance Optimization

### Image Optimization

- **Next.js Image Component:** Always use `next/image` for images
- **Optimization:** Automatic optimization, lazy loading, responsive images
- **Formats:** Use WebP, AVIF when possible
- **Sizing:** Provide appropriate sizes for responsive images

### Code Splitting

- **Dynamic Imports:** Use `next/dynamic` for code splitting
- **Route-Based:** Automatic code splitting per route
- **Component-Level:** Lazy load heavy components

### Bundle Optimization

- **Tree Shaking:** Remove unused code
- **Minification:** Automatic in production builds
- **Compression:** Enable gzip/brotli compression
- **Bundle Analysis:** Use `@next/bundle-analyzer` to monitor size

### Media Optimization

- **Videos:** Compress, use appropriate formats (MP4, WebM)
- **Lazy Loading:** Implement for below-the-fold content
- **CDN:** Use CDN for static assets
- **Caching:** Implement proper cache headers

### Performance Targets

- **Lighthouse Score:** 90+ for Performance
- **First Contentful Paint:** < 1.8s
- **Largest Contentful Paint:** < 2.5s
- **Time to Interactive:** < 3.8s
- **Cumulative Layout Shift:** < 0.1

## Accessibility Standards

### WCAG Compliance

- **Target:** WCAG 2.1 Level AA compliance minimum
- **Level AAA:** Strive for where possible

### Implementation Guidelines

#### Semantic HTML

- Use proper HTML5 semantic elements (`<header>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<article>`, `<section>`, `<footer>`)
- Use appropriate heading hierarchy (h1 → h2 → h3)
- Use lists (`<ul>`, `<ol>`) for list content

#### ARIA Labels

- Use ARIA labels when semantic HTML isn't sufficient
- Ensure all interactive elements are accessible
- Use `aria-label`, `aria-labelledby`, `aria-describedby` appropriately
- Use `role` attributes when necessary

#### Keyboard Navigation

- All interactive elements must be keyboard accessible
- Visible focus indicators (outline, focus ring)
- Logical tab order
- Skip links for main content

#### Screen Reader Compatibility

- Descriptive alt text for all images
- Form labels associated with inputs
- Error messages associated with form fields
- Announce dynamic content changes

#### Color Contrast

- **Normal Text:** Minimum 4.5:1 contrast ratio
- **Large Text:** Minimum 3:1 contrast ratio (18pt+ or 14pt+ bold)
- **UI Components:** Minimum 3:1 contrast ratio
- Test with tools like WebAIM Contrast Checker

#### Testing

- Use ESLint JSX A11y plugin
- Test with screen readers (NVDA, JAWS, VoiceOver)
- Keyboard-only navigation testing
- Automated accessibility testing tools
- Manual testing checklist

## Browser Support

### Target Browsers

- **Modern Browsers:** Latest 2 versions of Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge
- **Mobile:** iOS Safari (latest 2 versions), Chrome Mobile (latest)
- **Progressive Enhancement:** Core functionality works everywhere, enhanced features for modern browsers

### Polyfills

- Use Next.js polyfills for required features
- Consider `@next/polyfill` for older browser support if needed
- Test on target browsers regularly

## Deployment

### Recommended Platform

- **Vercel:** Optimal for Next.js (made by Next.js team)
- **Alternative:** Netlify, AWS Amplify, or self-hosted

### Environment Variables

- Use `.env.local` for local development
- Use `.env.production` for production
- Never commit `.env` files to git
- Use Vercel/Netlify environment variable settings

### Build Process

- **Development:** `npm run dev`
- **Build:** `npm run build`
- **Start:** `npm start` (production server)
- **Lint:** `npm run lint`
- **Format:** `npm run format`

## Security

- **HTTPS:** Always use HTTPS in production
- **Environment Variables:** Never expose sensitive keys
- **Content Security Policy:** Implement CSP headers
- **XSS Protection:** Sanitize user inputs
- **Dependencies:** Keep dependencies updated, audit regularly

## Monitoring & Analytics

- **Google Analytics:** Integrated via react-ga4
- **Performance Monitoring:** Consider Vercel Analytics or similar
- **Error Tracking:** Consider Sentry or similar
- **Uptime Monitoring:** Monitor site availability
